[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating logging dependencies**\n\nI’m looking into why the runtime core isn’t compiling. There might be issues with how Gradle’s testImplementation includes runtime dependencies versus compile ones. I’m considering adding log4j-core for testing since it uses core classes, but that’s only if necessary. Alternatively, log4j-api could work since its ParameterizedMessage is public. But I’d need to ensure I’m covering the bridge’s throwable semantics effectively. I wonder if I can instantiate Log4jLogger with a mock ExtendedLogger to capture Messages, but creating stubs may not be possible.\n\n**Exploring logging options**\n\nI'm trying to figure out the limitations on creating source stubs for library APIs, as they’re forbidden. So, I wonder if I could use inner test fakes or something less broad like a custom AbstractLogger from Log4j-api. Oh, but no luck with that. It seems that using log4j-core might be a better option since I can add it as a test implementation and utilize public core configurations. I need to make sure I’m version agnostic, though. Would configuring via system properties be a solution? There are core classes available, but do I need a native image?\n\n**Considering custom appenders**\n\nI’m thinking about adding a custom test appender class, even if it could require some metadata from the core. But I want to keep it simple and avoid any extra complexity. The easiest fix might be to remove the factory test and instead use the public ParameterizedMessage for my tests. That way, I can still check for the same semantics and maintain some level of coverage, even if it doesn’t cover the bridge class directly.\n\n**Evaluating log4j API usage**\n\nI’m looking into whether the ParameterizedMessage constructors in log4j-api are deprecated, especially for version 3.0.0-alpha1. I might need to check the log4j-api sources, but I need to focus strictly on open-source files related to the error output. It seems that I could consider using MessageFactory2 instead, as ParameterizedMessageFactory may still be valid. Log4j 2 shows that ParameterizedMessage constructors detect exceptions in their arguments, which is important for handling errors.\n\n**Analyzing ParameterizedMessage usage**\n\nI'm examining how LocationAwareLog uses the new ParameterizedMessage constructor. It appears to rely on the throwable being detected correctly, especially if it's null. I’m considering renaming a test to reflect how Log4jLogger behaves. The old test had simpler messages, but I might need to use SimpleMessage or ObjectMessage for better coverage. I’m also pondering whether I should check the source for version 2.24.3 to find replaced classes. It could be useful to search through the repository for any references to ThrowableConsuming to clarify this.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_085f145bcf7f6d4c016a0d730a72288195931bda927c32c957\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqDXMas0UWFZeFumilWkKjOmTSw5u6d2Gdw0iEM7zugmkCcSMcp1EFsqRScK6vgkCrb3di9tedWTdy2VFiRgH5HG0wEx4JqzIH7IFvMh35p356c0IFrMqcf-szB8pa1JnTW3RIEEaIkNwacMapbo27PrsI0--eueN30BkRaQdoqKhqtkunIow9fcqLFohv4192LD7KGdxqIA5PrBpQzk6T6FZpF5Zyh7cMXuIZBaJv4OLjI_yh9P6VP4-QKJdPlBTyOMP7rQuUyUzKgecTuPOTxTIGZqP8lHvmhTdLaCLI5OAGV_YSEbN6_UqmQsvqXNLBzzou9ClxLLeoIPeuystqxENz6oHAEUhlmtcgaBB7vSyVWSk7yHCkpKFgD6bnjPmYk0Q6vtWkT-cwVW_XSsEBW5WgJwplKlgnEoh4r7OaikYJ2rkLvsW64uPgiK64Mm7lLHflPntSpzrgcD2s6xKFZADbEIcDvtaSwbhrNJTGWWq7eK2DKqD7gi_85ncMfffzHZOLhvMZEBBD4hULQK3TROXmI8iw2MUMIEe1KOip3Et1OBCXMx6m9llJrrFZTriH2eVgzGBjkikr8X_D1SW-Lz8QXAr26qGlh9kyqG5KV59GhcaeVEtBx-Hs05aClT660ssUrty3_ywitihofxpDScMMFCiuwlSlzuNgzyHAXwLWPoNhiZlF0U3w6lX7ypU4j82qSvpK3A3Yh6iHD_f37PbEwl14m1pJ_2DF-BIxyGL8D7P_Xem8hzjfoHgfkxb3-nrtEnTKMDGt_JTSsAQ-_QP7IzRK4RljIDx-3Xingt90DBtULUJKkHP6LkiEdgUNa1n4rCaOIXgAHjYqlZlb0dmXLeRdwThrUX207rOI1LU4nW1j8Za3Ql295vKnZElYxX06uTdonKIwSjJ6sWszBRXaiJ-nGWP3QEdAm1ygzTNgnfOsT_PHY9hcdzJuo